URCM vs Transformer Encoder Benchmark (Full Detail)

Purpose
- Compare CPU-only runtime characteristics of two encoder backends used inside URCM:
  - URCM Recurrent (numpy echo-state with gating and tanh dynamics)
  - Transformer Stub (lightweight Q/K/V projections; baseline only, not a production transformer)

Environment
- OS: Windows (win32)
- Python: 3.13.3
- CPU-only, no GPU
- Libraries: numpy, scipy (installed via requirements.txt)

Methodology
- Input sequence: random normal vectors, shape (seq_len, input_dim)
- Parameters:
  - input_dim = 24
  - resonance_dim = 64
  - seq_len = 64
  - runs = 50
- Process:
  - Initialize encoders:
    - Recurrent: ResonancePathEncoder(..., encoder_type='recurrent_numpy')
    - Transformer: ResonancePathEncoder(..., encoder_type='transformer_stub')
  - For each backend:
    - Run encode_path(vectors) runs times
    - Measure total elapsed time with perf_counter
    - Compute:
      - latency_ms = total_ms / runs
      - throughput_ops_s = runs / total_seconds
- Determinism:
  - Transformer stub initializes with a fixed seed (42), recurrent weights may load trained matrices if available; otherwise random init is used.

Results (Measured)
- URCM Recurrent:
  - latency_ms ≈ 1.580348
  - throughput_ops_s ≈ 632.77
- Transformer Stub:
  - latency_ms ≈ 0.062614
  - throughput_ops_s ≈ 15,970.87

