Interpretation
- The transformer stub is a very small, CPU-friendly attention projection and runs faster than the recurrent encoder on this micro-benchmark.
- The recurrent encoder performs echo-state dynamics, gating, and tanh nonlinearity, which adds compute cost.
- These numbers reflect speed only. They do not assert semantic quality, accuracy, or stability comparisons.

Encoder Internals (Technical)
- URCM Recurrent:
  - State update per step: s_t = tanh(W_in·x_t + W_res·s_{t-1} + b), with last-step gating
    - Gate: g = σ(α·||W_in·x_t|| - β·||W_res·s_{t-1}||), scales input term on final step
  - Matrices:
    - W_in ∈ R^{InputDim×ResDim}, W_res ∈ R^{ResDim×ResDim}, W_out ∈ R^{ResDim×InputDim}, b ∈ R^{ResDim}
  - Decoding (not used in this benchmark): atanh inversion, W_res_inv, and snapping for stability
- Transformer Stub:
  - Projections: Q = X·W_q, K = X·W_k, V = X·W_v with W_q,W_k ∈ R^{InputDim×32}, W_v ∈ R^{InputDim×ResDim}
  - Query selection: the last vector acts as the global query
  - Scores: softmax(K·q / √32), Context: Σ w_i·V_i, Output: tanh(Context)

Complexity (Approximate)
- Recurrent (per sequence):
  - O(SeqLen·(InputDim·ResDim + ResDim²)) for W_in and W_res products
  - Additional scalar norms and tanh are linear in ResDim
- Transformer Stub (per sequence):
  - O(SeqLen·InputDim·32) for Q,K + O(SeqLen·InputDim·ResDim) for V
  - O(SeqLen·32) for attention scores and O(SeqLen·ResDim) for weighted sum
  - Typically faster when ResDim² dominates recurrent echo cost

Memory Footprint (Matrices)
- Recurrent:
  - W_in: 24×64, W_res: 64×64, W_out: 64×24, b: 64
- Transformer Stub:
  - W_q: 24×32, W_k: 24×32, W_v: 24×64
Note: Actual byte usage depends on dtype (float32 vs float64) and BLAS configuration.

Measurement Considerations
- Warm-up: none; repeated runs (50) average out transient costs
- BLAS: numpy may use multi-threading; CPU scheduling and power states can affect times
- Weights: if trained weights found (urcm_weights.pkl), recurrent may print load message and recalc W_res_inv; if mismatch, random init is used
- Determinism: fixed seed for transformer stub, recurrent behavior depends on weight load

Limitations
- Transformer “stub” is not a full transformer architecture; it is intended as a lightweight baseline.
- CPU-only; results can vary by hardware and Python/numpy builds.
- Single-sequence micro-benchmark; no batching or end-to-end pipeline costs included.

Reproduce Locally
- One-liner:
  - python -c "from urcm.core.performance import PerformanceBenchmark; b=PerformanceBenchmark(); print(b.benchmark_encoder_latency_comparison())"
- Python snippet:
  - from urcm.core.performance import PerformanceBenchmark
  - b = PerformanceBenchmark()
  - results = b.benchmark_encoder_latency_comparison(input_dim=24, resonance_dim=64, seq_len=64, runs=50)
  - print(results)

